{"cursor":"10404","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\n\n of a heart viewed from the apex (top), showing the apical part of the\n ventricles removed and the mitral valve clearly visible. Due to missing data\n the leaflets of the tricuspid and aortic valves are not clearly visible, but\n the openings are; the pulmonary valve is not visible. On the left are two\n standard 2D views (taken from the 3D dataset) showing tricuspid and mitral\n valves (above) and aortal valve (below).]]\n\nA 'heart valve' normally allows blood flow in only one direction through the\nheart. The four valves commonly represented in a mammalian heart determine the\npathway of blood flow through the heart. A heart valve opens or closes incumbent\nupon differential blood pressure on each side.\n  \n\nThe four valves in the heart are: not counting the valve of the coronary\nsinus, and the valve of the inferior vena cava\n* The two atrioventricular (AV) valves, which are between the atria and the\n  ventricles, are the mitral valve and the tricuspid valve.\n* The two semilunar (SL) valves, which are in the arteries leaving the heart,\n  are the aortic valve and the pulmonary valve.\n\nA form of heart disease occurs when a valve malfunctions and allows some blood\nto flow in the wrong direction. This is called regurgitation.\n","linknr":325,"url":"Heart_valve","recorded":1362506215,"links":46,"instances":["medicine","fluid_dynamics","anatomy"],"pdf":[],"categories":["Cardiac anatomy","Valves"],"headings":["Atrioventricular or cuspid valves","Semilunar valves","Heart valve dynamics","See also","Notes","External links"],"image":["//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/9/99/Question_book-new.svg/50px-Question_book-new.svg.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/61/Apikal4D.gif/300px-Apikal4D.gif","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf10/skins/common/images/magnify-clip.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/4/4a/Apikal4D_explained.png","//bits.wikimedia.org/stati